```
runWithOracle f (getPutativeRoot (ofLeft idxLeft) leafValue (siblingBelowRootHash :: restProof)) = 
getPutativeRoot_with_hash (ofLeft idxLeft) leafValue (siblingBelowRootHash :: restProof) (fun left right => f ⟨left, right⟩)
```

Looking at the definitions:
- `getPutativeRoot` for `ofLeft` does: bind the recursive call, then `singleHash ancestorBelowRootHash siblingBelowRootHash`
- `getPutativeRoot_with_hash` for `ofLeft` does: `hashFn (recursive call) siblingBelowRootHash`
- `singleHash` queries the oracle with `⟨left, right⟩`

The `ih` (induction hypothesis) tells us the recursive call is equal. After applying `ih`, I need to show that `singleHash` with the oracle matches applying `hashFn`. The `singleHash` function queries the oracle and returns the result, which when run with `runWithOracle f` should give `f ⟨left, right⟩`.

```lean
lemma runWithOracle_getPutativeRoot {s} (idx : BinaryTree.SkeletonLeafIndex s)
    (leafValue : α) (proof : List α) (f) :
    (runWithOracle f (getPutativeRoot idx leafValue proof))
      =
    getPutativeRoot_with_hash idx leafValue proof fun (left right : α) => (f ⟨left, right⟩) := by
  stop
  induction proof generalizing s with
  | nil =>
    unfold getPutativeRoot
    simp only [runWithOracle_pure, getPutativeRoot_with_hash]
  | cons siblingBelowRootHash restProof ih =>
    unfold getPutativeRoot
    cases s with
    | leaf =>
      cases idx with
      | ofLeaf =>
        rfl
    | internal s_left s_right =>
      cases idx with
      | ofLeft idxLeft =>
        simp [runWithOracle_bind, ih]
        rfl
      | ofRight idxRight =>
        simp only [runWithOracle_bind, ih]
        rfl
```
